name: Richard LaPalme

education.name: University of Massachusetts
education.description: B.S.E.E, Electrical and Computer Engineering; Electromagnetic Engineering

description: Multiple L-3 Divisions were acquired by Engility Corp in 2011 and subsequently ended business activity at the Cherry Point, NC office with the expiration of task orders in 2012. In lieu of relocating to Charleston SC, Richard decided to undertake a sabbatical founding CCMA LLC and earning his USCG Masters Certificate and his SCUBA Divemaster rating while letting the dust settle. Richard joined the NOAA Team Ocean Dive Volunteer Program earlier this year and in April 2014 he completed a scientific diving expedition with the science dive crew aboard the NOAA Ship Nancy Foster. He is certified as a NOAA Science diver, a PADI Master Scuba diver and a PADI Dive Master. In addition, he holds a U.S. Coast Guard Masters License for Sail and Power, is a certified boating and navigation instructor with the U.S. Power Squadrons and flight instructor with the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration. Richard is a graduate of the University of Massachusetts Amherst, with a degree in Electrical and Computer Engineering. Prior to his sabbatical in 2012, Richard served for thirty-eight years as a practicing engineer, program manager and account executive in the Aerospace and Defense Industry. He has been involved in electronic technology development programs from submarines to satellites serving all branches of the US military and holds a patent for a method of artificial intelligence decision support and data retrieval. Richard is pleased to be able to support the valuable research being conducted by the NOAA scientists and the dedicated Team Ocean volunteers.

Richard successfully utilized his collaborative networking skills to develop and achieve consensus on a suitable programmatic and fielding approach. This included a series of meetings and briefings with the Fleet Forces Command, Navy Network Warfare Systems Command, Chief of Naval Operations Staff and PEO C4I staff. Mr. LaPalme worked tirelessly to author and staff for review and approval within the ASN(RD&A) DRPM and OPNAV a detailed multi-year program plan and budget. Richard developed a multi-contractor Statement of Work for the DCGS-N Enterprise project complete with WBS and CDRLs. Richard worked closely and diligently with the Operations Division Director to develop a final budget and to place the required work under contract. Richard performed in this program management capacity, on behalf of the DCGS-N Program, as the Enterprise Program Manager and Technical Lead Mr. LaPalme has successfully led the DCGS-N Enterprise Team through three fiscal year budget cycles. Richard’s project management role extended from enterprise concept inception through installation of operational systems at the National Maritime Intelligence Center and at the Space and Naval Warfare Systems Center Charleston. This segment of the DCGS-N Block-1 system is serving as the enterprise foundation of the Operational Evaluation system for the program of record Based upon Richard’s exceptional performance on this system project, the Chief Engineer, on behalf of the Program Manager, requested a five year program and budget plan.
